**1. camelCase Format:**
- Start with lowercase letter
- Capitalize first letter of each new word
- No spaces or underscores
- **Used for:** variables, functions, methods, properties

**camelCase Examples:**
```javascript
var firstName = "John";
var lastName = "Doe";
var myAge = 25;
var userEmailAddress = "john@example.com";

function calculateTotalPrice() {
    // code here
}

function getUserData() {
    // code here
}
```

**2. PascalCase Format:**
- Start with uppercase letter
- Capitalize first letter of each new word
- No spaces or underscores
- **Used for:** classes, constructors, components

**PascalCase Examples:**
```javascript
class UserProfile {
    constructor(name) {
        this.name = name;
    }
}

class BookController {
    getAllBooks() {
        // code here
    }
}

function CarFactory() {
    // constructor function
}

// React components
function UserDashboard() {
    return <div>Dashboard</div>;
}
```

**3. snake_case Format:**
- All lowercase letters
- Words separated by underscores
- **Used for:** database fields, constants, file names

**snake_case Examples:**
```javascript
// Database fields
const user_data = {
    first_name: "John",
    last_name: "Doe",
    email_address: "john@example.com"
};

// Constants
const MAX_RETRY_COUNT = 5;
const API_BASE_URL = "https://api.example.com";

// File names
// user_service.js
// data_processor.js
// api_client.js
```

**Quick Comparison:**
```javascript
// camelCase - variables/functions
let userName = "John";
function getUserData() {}

// PascalCase - classes/components  
class UserProfile {}
function UserComponent() {}

// snake_case - constants/database
const MAX_USER_COUNT = 100;
const first_name = "John";
```

**When to Use Each:**
- **camelCase**: Variables, functions, methods, object properties
- **PascalCase**: Classes, constructors, React components
- **snake_case**: Database fields, constants, configuration keys
- **UPPER_SNAKE_CASE**: Constants (MAX_SIZE, DEFAULT_TIMEOUT)

**Why These Conventions Matter:**
- Standard convention in JavaScript/TypeScript
- Easy to read without spaces
- Distinguishes different types of identifiers
- Improves code consistency and team collaboration

**Editing List Items with DOM Manipulation**

You can edit list items by selecting them and modifying their properties.

**Example:**
```javascript
const choice = document.querySelectorAll(".choice");
for (let i = 0; i < choice.length; i++) {
    choice[i].style.backgroundColor = "orange";
    choice[i].style.color = "purple";
    choice[i].style.fontSize = "5rem";
    choice[i].style.fontWeight = "5rem";
};
```

**How it works:**
- **Select all items:** Use `querySelectorAll` to get all elements with class "choice"
- **Loop through:** Use a `for` loop to iterate through each element
- **Modify styles:** Change `backgroundColor`, `color`, `fontSize`, `fontWeight` for each item
- **Apply changes:** Each list item gets the new styling

**Key concepts:**
- **Multiple elements:** `querySelectorAll` returns a NodeList
- **Loop iteration:** Use `for` loop to access each element
- **Style properties:** Modify CSS properties using `style.property`
- **Bulk changes:** Apply same changes to multiple elements
- **Index access:** Use `[i]` to access each element in the loop

