A Promise is an object representing the eventual completion or failure of an async operation. It has states: pending, fulfilled, or rejected.

Creating a Promise:
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  if (everythingIsGood) {
    resolve('Success value');
  } else {
    reject('Error value');
  }
});

Using a Promise:
promise.then(result => {
  console.log('Got:', result);
});
promise.catch(error => {
  console.log('Error:', error);
});
// resolve/reject is for inside the Promise, .then/.catch is for outside.

In a Promise chain, the parameter inside .then() receives what was passed to resolve(...) in your Promise. The parameter inside .catch() gets whatever was sent to reject(...).

Example:

promise
  .then(value => {
    // 'value' is what resolve(...) sent
    console.log('Success:', value);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    // 'error' is what reject(...) sent
    console.log('Failure:', error);
  });

If resolve('done!') runs, .then() receives 'done!'. If reject('fail!'), .catch gets 'fail!'.

Summary:
- parameter in .then() = value from resolve
- parameter in .catch() = value from reject

You can chain Promises by returning a new promise (or value) from each .then(). Each .then() waits until the previous promise resolves. If any promise rejects, execution goes immediately to .catch().

Step-by-step example:

const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  resolve('Well Done! Promise One is Resolved');
});

const promiseTwo = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  resolve('Well Done! Promise Two is Resolved');
});
const promiseThree = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  reject('Promise Three is Rejected. Unlucky!');
});

promise
  .then((value) => {
    console.log(value); // Logs from promise one
    return promiseTwo; // Return the next promise
  })
  .then((value) => {
    console.log(value); // Logs promise two result
    return promiseThree;
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.log(error); // Handles promise three's rejection, or any earlier error
  });

Each .then() gets the previous result. If you return a new value instead of a Promise, the next .then() runs immediately with that value. If a promise is rejected, .catch() runs, and later .then() handlers are skipped.

You can run concurrent Promises using Promise.all. Pass it an array of Promises. It waits for all of them to resolve before running .then() with an array of results. If any promise rejects, .catch() is called right away and gives the error.

Example:

const promiseOne = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => {
    resolve('Promise One Resolved!');
  }, 2000);
});
const promiseTwo = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => {
    resolve('Promise Two Resolved!');
  }, 1500);
});
Promise.all([promiseOne, promiseTwo])
  .then(data => console.log(data, data))
  .catch(error => console.log(error));

How it works: Results are in order, matching the input array. If any promise fails, no results are returned, only the first error. Other promises still run, but you won't receive their values

