**JavaScript Inheritance: Prototypes vs Classes**

**🏗️ Prototype-Based Inheritance:**

**What is .prototype?**
Every JavaScript function has a `prototype` property. When you use a function as a constructor (with `new`), all created objects inherit from this prototype object.

**Basic Prototype Example:**
```javascript
function Vehicle(brand, year) {
  this.brand = brand;
  this.year = year;
}

// Add method to prototype - shared by all instances
Vehicle.prototype.drive = function() {
  console.log(`${this.brand} is driving`);
};

// Add another method later
Vehicle.prototype.getAge = function() {
  return new Date().getFullYear() - this.year;
};

// Create instances
const car1 = new Vehicle('Toyota', 2020);
const car2 = new Vehicle('Honda', 2022);

car1.drive(); // "Toyota is driving"
car2.drive(); // "Honda is driving"
console.log(car1.getAge()); // 4 (current year - 2020)
```

**Prototype Chain:**
```javascript
console.log(car1.__proto__ === Vehicle.prototype); // true
console.log(Vehicle.prototype.__proto__ === Object.prototype); // true
console.log(car1.toString()); // Inherited from Object.prototype
```

**Method Overriding:**
```javascript
// Instance property shadows prototype
car1.drive = function() {
  console.log(`${this.brand} is driving FAST!`);
};

car1.drive(); // "Toyota is driving FAST!" (instance method)
car2.drive(); // "Honda is driving" (prototype method)
```

**👑 Class-Based Inheritance (Modern):**

**The extends Keyword:**
`extends` creates a parent-child relationship between classes, where the child inherits all properties and methods from the parent.

**Basic Class Inheritance:**
```javascript
class Animal {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  speak() {
    console.log(`${this.name} makes a sound`);
  }

  eat() {
    console.log(`${this.name} is eating`);
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  constructor(name, breed) {
    super(name); // Call parent constructor
    this.breed = breed;
  }

  // Override parent method
  speak() {
    console.log(`${this.name} barks!`);
  }

  // Add new method
  fetch() {
    console.log(`${this.name} fetches the ball`);
  }
}

// Usage
const dog = new Dog('Rex', 'Golden Retriever');
dog.speak(); // "Rex barks!" (overridden method)
dog.eat();   // "Rex is eating" (inherited method)
dog.fetch(); // "Rex fetches the ball" (new method)
```

**🔗 Inheritance Chain Comparison:**

**Prototype Chain:**
```javascript
function Parent(name) {
  this.name = name;
}
Parent.prototype.greet = function() {
  return `Hello, ${this.name}`;
};

function Child(name, age) {
  Parent.call(this, name); // "Super" equivalent
  this.age = age;
}

// Set up inheritance
Child.prototype = Object.create(Parent.prototype);
Child.prototype.constructor = Child;

Child.prototype.getAge = function() {
  return this.age;
};
```

**Class Inheritance (Cleaner):**
```javascript
class Parent {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  greet() {
    return `Hello, ${this.name}`;
  }
}

class Child extends Parent {
  constructor(name, age) {
    super(name); // Cleaner "super" call
    this.age = age;
  }

  getAge() {
    return this.age;
  }
}
```

**🎯 Practical Examples:**

**Vehicle Inheritance Hierarchy:**
```javascript
class Vehicle {
  constructor(make, model, year) {
    this.make = make;
    this.model = model;
    this.year = year;
  }

  getInfo() {
    return `${this.year} ${this.make} ${this.model}`;
  }

  start() {
    console.log(`${this.getInfo()} is starting...`);
  }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
  constructor(make, model, year, doors) {
    super(make, model, year);
    this.doors = doors;
  }

  honk() {
    console.log('Beep beep!');
  }
}

class ElectricCar extends Car {
  constructor(make, model, year, doors, range) {
    super(make, model, year, doors);
    this.range = range;
  }

  // Override start method
  start() {
    console.log(`${this.getInfo()} is starting silently...`);
  }

  getRange() {
    return `${this.range} miles`;
  }
}

// Usage
const tesla = new ElectricCar('Tesla', 'Model 3', 2023, 4, 350);
tesla.start();    // "2023 Tesla Model 3 is starting silently..."
tesla.honk();     // "Beep beep!" (inherited from Car)
console.log(tesla.getRange()); // "350 miles"
```

**🔄 Under the Hood:**

**Prototypes are still there:**
```javascript
class MyClass {
  method() {}
}

console.log(typeof MyClass); // "function"
console.log(MyClass.prototype.method); // The method function
```

**Static Methods & Properties:**
```javascript
class MathUtils {
  static PI = 3.14159;

  static calculateArea(radius) {
    return this.PI * radius * radius;
  }
}

// Called on class, not instances
console.log(MathUtils.calculateArea(5)); // 78.53975
```

**📊 When to Use Each:**

- **Use Classes** for new code - cleaner syntax, better tooling
- **Understand Prototypes** for debugging and working with legacy code
- **Prototypes** are still fundamental - classes are syntactic sugar

**Key Differences:**
- **Classes** use `extends` and `super` for inheritance
- **Prototypes** use manual prototype chain setup
- **Classes** have built-in constructor validation
- **Both** ultimately use the prototype system underneath

**💡 Best Practices:**
1. Use `class` syntax for new projects
2. Call `super()` before using `this` in derived classes
3. Use `static` for utility methods that don't need instance data
4. Understand the prototype chain for advanced debugging
5. Consider composition over complex inheritance hierarchies

You can use window.localStorage.setItem or just localStorage.setItem:

