A static method in JavaScript belongs to the class itself, not to instances of that class. That means you call it on the class, not on an object made with that class.

Example:

class MathUtils {
  static add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
  }
}

MathUtils.add(2, 3); // ✅ works

const obj = new MathUtils();
obj.add(2, 3); // ❌ error: add is not a function

Why? The method add is defined static, so it can only be called as MathUtils.add. This is good for utility functions that do not need instance data.

Polymorphism means different classes have methods with the same name but different behavior. One function name, multiple forms.

Example:
class Animal {
  speak() { console.log("Animal makes a sound"); }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
  speak() { console.log("Woof!"); }
}
class Cat extends Animal {
  speak() { console.log("Meow!"); }
}
function makeAnimalSpeak(animal) {
  animal.speak();
}
makeAnimalSpeak(new Dog()); // Woof!
makeAnimalSpeak(new Cat()); // Meow!

Why does this matter? You can write code that works on a generic class, and the right version (child or parent) is called depending on the object.

splice() is an array method that lets you add, remove, or replace items in-place:
Syntax: array.splice(start, deleteCount, item1, item2, ...);

start: Where to begin changing the array (index)
deleteCount: How many items to remove
item1, item2: Optional, what to add in their place

Examples:
// Remove items
let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "orange", "kiwi"];
fruits.splice(1, 2); // removes 'banana', 'orange'
console.log(fruits); // ["apple", "kiwi"]

// Add items
fruits.splice(1, 0, "banana", "orange"); // adds back at index 1
console.log(fruits); // ["apple", "banana", "orange", "kiwi"]

// Replace items
fruits.splice(1, 2, "grape", "pear");
console.log(fruits); // ["apple", "grape", "pear", "kiwi"]

