e.target is the actual element that was clicked or triggered the event—possibly a child deep inside.
e.currentTarget is always the element the event listener was attached to.

Example:
<div id="parent">
  <button id="child"><span>Click me</span></button>
</div>
const childBtn = document.getElementById('child');
childBtn.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  console.log('target:', e.target); // Could be <span>
  console.log('currentTarget:', e.currentTarget); // Always the <button>
});

If you click on the <span>, e.target is <span>, but e.currentTarget is <button>, since that's where the listener sits.

